>2つの銀行のそれぞれは20日にやったお偉いさんの集まりで、2022年9月28日に皆で決めた紙に書いた約束によって、二つの銀行が出している「銀行が儲かったらその分お金あげるから、買ってね券」を交換っこして、その券を使って上の会社を作り、長野銀行をさっきの券を使って下っ端の会社にするってことを決めたよ。両方とも券を交換する約束と「これから一緒にやっていくよ」という約束をしたよ。
>券を買ってくれた人へあげるお金の割合は長野銀行の券一枚分だけど八十二銀行の券は2.54枚分だよ

One additonal thing about the word order:
Statement:
>It's going to rain tomorow.
>Morgen wird es regnen.
>Zajtra bude pršať.
Questioning the statement (disbelief, shock):
>It's going to rain tomorrow?!
>Morgen wird es regnen?!
>Zajtra bude pršať? (Less shock, but still questioning prior information)
Question (No prior information about potential rain):
>Is it going to rain tomorrow?
>Wird es morgen regnen?
>Bude zajtra pršať?
From what you're saying this distiction doesn't happen in Russian, or alternatively, is expressed differently. Is that correct?

Thinking about it, adding ли is probably only a factor in written text, since the question would be signified by rising tone in speech anyway.

How come only some words have a locative case?
Slovak always has only one case for locative + prepositional, called the locative. Interestingly, sometimes the ending matches with Russian prepositional (мёд - med, o мёдe - o mede, в мёдy - v mede), but sometimes Russian locative (бepeг - breh, o бepeгe - o brehu, нa бepeгy - na brehu).

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>176844055
>And how is accusative not the second case then?
Genitive comes directly after just any noun, so it was placed after nominative. Dative very often comes before the verb. Accusative comes after the verb. Then instrumental and/or locative. Then vocative either comes at the beginning or end of a sentence so they put it at the end to respect the idea of nominative being first.

>>176837985
This is the case with Catholic cultural sphere, obviously not everywhere, educated languages are different in different areas of the world. Russia more or less made up its own Church Slavonic sphere in early modern times, and numerous borrowings from there are completely assimilated, so there's no educated insertions in Latin or any other languages.

>How come only some words have a locative case?
That's not a full case since, indeed, not every word can be declined by it, it exists only in closed class of old nouns. Probably stems out from merger of Proto-Slavic/Old Russian declension classes as others have pointed out, which seems to not happened/proceeded differently in Slovak. There's also a partitive form used instead of genitive for some words, and it's somewhat productive even today (classic example - выпeй чaю - "tea" is obviously a relatively modern borrowing and have developed a partitive).

Sedan, mitt i meningen, kommer det omisskännliga ljudet genom mikrofonen och in i våra öron. Hon slutar genast att tala, oförmögen att bearbeta det som just hände tillräckligt snabbt för att kunna spela bort det. Förlägenheten överväldigar henne snabbt när chatten översvämmas av GuraMM, och hennes modell blir slapp när hon backar undan från datorn. Allt du hör är ett tyst "Herregud" från några meter bort när hon försöker samla sig. Hon försöker rädda situationen genom att säga saker som "c'mooon chat, säger du att detta aldrig har hänt dig förut? Det var isen!". Men innerst inne dör hon inombords i vetskapen om att det omedelbart kommer att klippas och att varje chumbud från jordens alla hörn snart kommer att höra hennes explosiva flatulens.

Got any knorr chicken stock cubes? Get some. Mash one up with olive oil to make a paste, rub it all over the bird. Salt & pepper, into a baking tray with a cm of water in the bottom and tin foil on top. 160 fan 180 conventional for an hour, basting a few times. Then temp right up to 200 fan 210ish conventional and more salt on the skin, tin foil off, give it half an hour at that heat. Can cook it with your eye, if the skin looks golden brown and crispy the bird will be cooked and still moist underneath too. Let it rest for half an hour while you use the baking tray to make a nice gravy. Scrape up the burnt fat and stuff by deglazing with white wine and reduce/burn the booze off. Put some veggie water in and fresh parsley, bit of flour to thicken if needed. Bosh.
